<div id="review_1077864913" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1077864913" />
    <a title="Tandava Graham" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14426279-tandava-graham"><img alt="Tandava Graham" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1352486560p2/14426279.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1077864913?book_show_action=true">Oct 11, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tandava Graham" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tandava Graham" href="/user/show/14426279-tandava-graham">Tandava Graham</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 0141310812" href="/book/show/23356226-the-brothers-lionheart">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14426279-tandava-graham?shelf=spiritual-fiction">spiritual-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14426279-tandava-graham?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14426279-tandava-graham?shelf=middle-grade">middle-grade</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1077864913" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10670726382057825175">For years I&apos;ve had a strong but vaguely-detailed memory of a book I read as a child. I couldn&apos;t remember the title, the author, the plot, or even how old I was when I read it. I knew that a boy followed his brother to a land after death, and I had a blurry image of what was possibly the cover, and I knew that younger-me had been deeply moved by it in some way. Every few years I&apos;d try to find it, but without any luck. <br/><br/>A few weeks ago, I found it. I must have have finally hit on the right search t</span>
  <span id="freeText10670726382057825175" style="display:none">For years I've had a strong but vaguely-detailed memory of a book I read as a child. I couldn't remember the title, the author, the plot, or even how old I was when I read it. I knew that a boy followed his brother to a land after death, and I had a blurry image of what was possibly the cover, and I knew that younger-me had been deeply moved by it in some way. Every few years I'd try to find it, but without any luck. <br /><br />A few weeks ago, I found it. I must have have finally hit on the right search terms, or else the Wikipedia page for the book was created or updated since my last attempt. I looked through all the covers on GoodReads, and didn't recognize any of them, but I was still 90% sure. But when I ordered a used copy sight-unseen from AbeBooks, it arrived with what I instantly knew was the right cover. (I added this edition and cover to GoodReads.)<br /><br />So anyway, I saved it for a free Saturday, and finally just sat down and read it cover-to-cover. I felt like I read it with two minds: the older-me watching the younger-me rediscovering it with a sense of awe. It's unusual and beautiful and simple and epic all at once. <br /><br />The relationship between the two brothers is very sweet, and the contrast between the two boys themselves lets them illustrate an ideal form of brotherly love from two different angles. Any kid who's a sibling should read this book if only for that. Another major theme is bravery. Jonathan is the hero of the events, and may seem overly idealized in his perfection. But it's Karl's story, and he's the one who manages to perform his own small acts of bravery in spite of his fear, inspired entirely by love for (and from) his brother. In fact, I would say that Jonathan represents the Guru, incarnating as a human and facing human challenges, but only for our benefit, to teach us how to be like him. Reincarnation is another theme: how death is just a transition to another life, and not to be feared. <br /><br />I honestly can't recall what I made of all this as a child, but it does make sense now why I retained such a feeling of depth and mystery about it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10670726382057825175" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


