<div id="review_1360727734" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1360727734" />
    <a title="Krista Claudine Baetiong" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong"><img alt="Krista Claudine Baetiong" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1552474554p2/13624574.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1360727734?book_show_action=true">Aug 11, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Krista Claudine Baetiong" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Krista Claudine Baetiong" href="/user/show/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong">Krista Claudine Baetiong</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong?shelf=childrens">childrens</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong?shelf=author-europe">author-europe</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong?shelf=literary-accolades">literary-accolades</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1360727734" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17182480938601881022">A tale about brotherly love and finding courage even in the most difficult of circumstances, <i> The Brothers Lionheart</i> narrates the adventures of two brothers, Jonathan and Karl Lionheart, as they dwell in an idyllic happy place called Nangiyala and confront the evil that starts to threaten the peace of the land.<br/><br/>Not long after Karl joins his older brother Jonathan in a secured border in Nangiyala called Cherry Farm, he learns that a cruel tyrant named Tengil has taken control of its adjacent neigh</span>
  <span id="freeText17182480938601881022" style="display:none">A tale about brotherly love and finding courage even in the most difficult of circumstances, <i> The Brothers Lionheart</i> narrates the adventures of two brothers, Jonathan and Karl Lionheart, as they dwell in an idyllic happy place called Nangiyala and confront the evil that starts to threaten the peace of the land.<br /><br />Not long after Karl joins his older brother Jonathan in a secured border in Nangiyala called Cherry Farm, he learns that a cruel tyrant named Tengil has taken control of its adjacent neighbor, Wild Rose Valley, and is merely waiting for the right moment when he can finally seize Cherry Farm and lay claim over the entire Nangiyala region. His brother has long joined the rebel forces to free Wild Rose Valley of tyranny and thwart Tengil’s evil plan. Karl is cowardly and has looked up to Jonathan for strength all his life, but his fear for his brother’s safety far outweighs the fear he feels for Tengil, and he soon joins Jonathan in the revolt. The rebellion ends up victorious, but not without several unhappy upshots that depict torture, betrayal, self-sacrifice and death. I also thought the book carries a political tone with its strong assertion of a radical change (through people’s war) in most part of the story; however, the ending confirms that it still clings on to the ideal.<br /> <br />There is something personal that endears me to this book: perhaps it reminds me of the own utopia I often sought out as a child whenever I felt lonely or scared or just wanted a sense of contentment, and where my definition of happiness is a room full of scented stationeries or having the ability to fly like Peter Pan. It reminds me of the realization I’d been hard-pressed to accept as a child—that I didn’t have enough money then to fill even a small box with stationeries, or that Peter Pan is only real in fantasyland. Or maybe, it also reminds me that valor can burn in the heart of even the most weak-hearted person like Karl. <br /><br />But this book mostly tells us not to pine for misery. It tells us that in order to get out of a wretched situation, it needs to be struggled with; that any person should have the courage to do whatever is necessary and to deal with whatever evil he or she faces, however difficult or precarious the situation. “There are things you have to do; otherwise, you are not a human being but just a bit of filth,” so says Jonathan Lionheart. <br /><br />Despite some serious overtones, <i>The Brothers Lionheart</i> is still a children’s book through and through with its moral values and the promise that there is a beautiful land of “campfires and sagas” waiting for us in the afterlife. It is a book I actually wished I had discovered early on; perhaps it could have saved me a lot of those Sylvia Plath quirks and feeling "just a bit of filth" growing up.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17182480938601881022" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

