<div id="review_691952393" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/691952393" />
    <a title="Orinoco Womble (tidy bag and all)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20738920-orinoco-womble-tidy-bag-and-all"><img alt="Orinoco Womble (tidy bag and all)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1406361683p2/20738920.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/691952393?book_show_action=true">Aug 11, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Orinoco Womble (tidy bag and all)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Orinoco Womble (tidy bag and all)" href="/user/show/20738920-orinoco-womble-tidy-bag-and-all">Orinoco Womble (tidy bag and all)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780192729040" href="/book/show/6875328-the-brothers-lionheart">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer691952393" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10217496347505799866">Another reviewer starts their review saying, <i>&quot;If you don&apos;t like this book, you just don&apos;t understand anything.&quot;</i> Well, that&apos;s one reader&apos;s opinion. Rather than be that harsh, I would say that if, like me, you grew up exclusively on the Pippi stories, <b>The Brothers Lionheart</b> will be rather a surprise. It&apos;s nothing like the Longstocking books, except in the fact that the children make their own decisions and take their own destinies in hand. From the moment that Jonathan saves his brother in a fire,</span>
  <span id="freeText10217496347505799866" style="display:none">Another reviewer starts their review saying, <i>"If you don't like this book, you just don't understand anything."</i> Well, that's one reader's opinion. Rather than be that harsh, I would say that if, like me, you grew up exclusively on the Pippi stories, <b>The Brothers Lionheart</b> will be rather a surprise. It's nothing like the Longstocking books, except in the fact that the children make their own decisions and take their own destinies in hand. From the moment that Jonathan saves his brother in a fire, both boys start to learn that "bravery" actually means "doing it scared."<br /><br />My mother used to say that if a children's book can't hold the interest of an adult, it probably won't be very interesting for children either, since children aren't stupid, they are just younger and shorter. There is plenty in this book to interest and intrigue the thinking adult--or the thinking child. However, it deals with a lot of tough topics such as death, tyranny and pain (both physical and emotional) so I would perhaps recommend it for older children, say 10-12. It's a quest story, an adventure story, and it even has a dragon and a seamonster. However the narration is a bit patchy in places, jumping over parts that I would have liked explained a bit better.<br /><br />I have to say that if I'd read this back in the days when I was laughing over Pippi's antics, I wouldn't have liked it at all--no, not even in 1973, when I was 11. Now, it made a good read. If a child you know and love reads it, make sure they know you're available to discuss it...you may be surprised.<br /><br />I had no idea Ms Lindgren had written so many books; how I wish more of them were available to me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10217496347505799866" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


